<h2>Overview</h2><p>If you're looking to improve the handling and ride quality of your 2004 Jeep TJ Wrangler, installing an Old Man Emu (OME) steering stabilizer can be a game-changer. This tutorial will guide you through the installation process while highlighting some useful tips and tricks to make the job easier.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>This article will detail:</p><ul><li>Necessary tools and materials</li><li>Step-by-step installation process</li><li>Helpful tips for avoiding common pitfalls</li><li>Key takeaways for maintaining your new stabilizer</li></ul><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><h3>Tools Needed</h3><p>Before you begin, gather the following tools and materials:</p><ul><li>Socket set (including 15mm and 18mm sockets)</li><li>Torque wrench</li><li>PB Blaster (or penetrating oil)</li><li>Ball joint spreader tool</li><li>Zip ties</li><li>Thread locker (as an alternative to lock washers)</li></ul><h3>Installation Steps</h3><ol><li><strong>Preparation:</strong> Begin by spraying PB Blaster on the bolts and allow it to soak for a few minutes to ease removal.</li><li><strong>Remove the old stabilizer:</strong> Start by removing the cotter pin from the castle nut. Use a 19mm socket to buzz off the nut. Since the bolt is a press-fit taper, use a ball joint spreader to assist in removal.</li><li><strong>Attach the new stabilizer:</strong> Orient the OME steering stabilizer into position. Make sure to capture it with a washer and nut. Instead of lock washers, apply thread locker to secure the bolts.</li><li><strong>Tightening:</strong> Torque the frame and tie rod bolts to approximately 50 ft/lbs and the top bolt on the stabilizer bushing to 35 ft/lbs. It's easier to torque these from the side you installed them on for better leverage.</li><li><strong>Finalize installation:</strong> Don't forget to replace the cotter pin and zip tie any necessary components to ensure everything is secured and tidy.</li></ol><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><p>Here are a few handy tips to keep in mind during your installation:</p><ul><li>Use a torque wrench to ensure proper tension on all bolts, avoiding the risk of damage.</li><li>Consider using thread locker wherever possible instead of lock washers, as it provides a more reliable hold and simplifies future removal.</li><li>If you've never worked with a ball joint spreader, practice on some spare parts prior to working on your Jeep to gain confidence.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>Installing an Old Man Emu steering stabilizer can greatly enhance the driveability of your Jeep TJ. With careful attention to detail in your installation process, you'll ensure that your Jeep remains on the road (or off it) without any unsettling issues. Remember to keep regular checks on your stabilizer post-installation to maintain optimal performance. Happy off-roading!</p>

